    {
      "id": "Nbk6muSKyfN8d1B1EsgBu",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 771.527103572982,
      "y": -3918.875786471289,
      "width": 4223.35400390625,
      "height": 630,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#6741d9",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2N",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1118418475,
      "version": 1726,
      "versionNonce": 1641637291,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1784240841454,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "We are given an integer and are supposed to return that integer number of rows of a pascal's triangle\nthe integer is between 1 and 30 both inclusive.\n\n1. Use math knowledge of Combinations and Binomial Theorem\n\nI know from studying maths that the rows of the pascal triangle corresponds to the coefficients of the binomial theorem expansion of that number\nlike say we're given n as the integer. then the i would return the list of coefficients for (a+b)^n where n goes from 0 to n-1 and in total have n \nnumber of rows of that pascal tree.\nfor each row the coefficients are just nCi where i varies from 0 to n and we have to calculate all such nCi for each n which goes from 0 to n-1 to actually\nget a total of n rows of the triangle. \nNow to actually get upto like 30 rows its difficult as to calculate nCi i would need factorials and that to upto like 30. so i was thinking to optimize calculating by using the factorial but cancelling\nthe larger numbers earlier on like i know nCi is just n!/i!*(n-1)! right for i can say nPi/i! also and i know nPi is just n* n-1 * n-2 ... ... ... n-i+1 so i can use a for loop for that.\nPlus i got to know about a java.math.BigInteger that actually makes our life easily by allowing us to perform arithematic on very big number. so i want to use this first then just try if i can get by with the loop optimization i though about.\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "We are given an integer and are supposed to return that integer number of rows of a pascal's triangle\nthe integer is between 1 and 30 both inclusive.\n\n1. Use math knowledge of Combinations and Binomial Theorem\n\nI know from studying maths that the rows of the pascal triangle corresponds to the coefficients of the binomial theorem expansion of that number\nlike say we're given n as the integer. then the i would return the list of coefficients for (a+b)^n where n goes from 0 to n-1 and in total have n \nnumber of rows of that pascal tree.\nfor each row the coefficients are just nCi where i varies from 0 to n and we have to calculate all such nCi for each n which goes from 0 to n-1 to actually\nget a total of n rows of the triangle. \nNow to actually get upto like 30 rows its difficult as to calculate nCi i would need factorials and that to upto like 30. so i was thinking to optimize calculating by using the factorial but cancelling\nthe larger numbers earlier on like i know nCi is just n!/i!*(n-1)! right for i can say nPi/i! also and i know nPi is just n* n-1 * n-2 ... ... ... n-i+1 so i can use a for loop for that.\nPlus i got to know about a java.math.BigInteger that actually makes our life easily by allowing us to perform arithematic on very big number. so i want to use this first then just try if i can get by with the loop optimization i though about.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "rHl3Myg-jdkR9T4AimD5q",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 771.4141778338214,
      "y": -3241.34866520803,
      "width": 4281.83349609375,
      "height": 270,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#6741d9",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2O",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1130185029,
      "version": 1180,
      "versionNonce": 1836137093,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1784242040594,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. Maintain pointers that traverse over the previous array to get the new array until desired numbers of rows are reached.\n\ni will have two pointer that calculate the sum taking two elements of the previous array at a time if the previous row has atleast two or more elements. i will use arraylist for this purpose.\nwhenever a new row is added it gets padded by 1s at the front and the back. The intial pascal triangle is just an arraylist containing an arraylist that just has 1 in it. but to reduce the number of checks if it has atleast two elements i would \nrather just make if cases that if the input is 1 return that arraylist. if it's 2 or more return the arraylist of arraylist that i have modified using this pointer approac\nh.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. Maintain pointers that traverse over the previous array to get the new array until desired numbers of rows are reached.\n\ni will have two pointer that calculate the sum taking two elements of the previous array at a time if the previous row has atleast two or more elements. i will use arraylist for this purpose.\nwhenever a new row is added it gets padded by 1s at the front and the back. The intial pascal triangle is just an arraylist containing an arraylist that just has 1 in it. but to reduce the number of checks if it has atleast two elements i would \nrather just make if cases that if the input is 1 return that arraylist. if it's 2 or more return the arraylist of arraylist that i have modified using this pointer approac\nh.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
